node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.text:
Photos by @francescolastrucci / The town of Cefalù on Sicily’s northern coast has a long history. The Greeks, Phoenicians, Romans, Arabs, and Normans all left traces. The town is dominated by an impressive rock and lapped by turquoise waters. I caught what is probably my favorite beach moment of the day, both for swimming and for photography: when the crowds are gone and the golden light of the sunset glows. 
Follow me @francescolastrucci for more places, daily life, and stories around the world. #sicily #italy #dailylife #summer

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / These are the colors of a beautiful Antarctic sunset. Have you ever wondered why the sky turns such magnificent colors at sunset and sunrise?
Sunlight is white because it contains all frequencies of visible light. Sunlight is also filtered by the air in the atmosphere. Light goes through different thicknesses of atmosphere and air particles, depending on the position of the sun, which in turn changes the sky’s color from blue (shorter light waves) to yellow, pink, orange, red, and purple (longer waves). This phenomenon is called atmospheric scattering. Basically, at sunset and sunrise, the light has to go through more air because of the low horizon of the sun. More atmosphere means more molecules that scatter the blue and violet away from your eyes, leaving only the other longer wave colors.
Follow me @DaisyGilardini for more images and stories behind the scenes. #sunset #iceberg #Antarctica #climatechange #climatechangeisreal

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / In northeast Greenland, the Crystal Palace cave is situated high above Grottedalen and yields stunning views looking northwest over the mighty valley below. Collecting calcite samples from this cave was one of the main objectives of the expedition. In 2015 we discovered several thick flowstone sequences that we couldn’t sample at the time because of a lack of resources. In 2019 we returned with coring and grinding equipment. We were careful to sample from naturally broken material where possible. Here, team member Chris Blakeley grinds a sample down into smaller pieces, while others in the background examine a potential sample to assess its suitability for paleoclimate work.

node.text: Photo by @kahliaprilphoto / There is a week in early spring when Lake Louise's water is crystal clear. It happens just after the winter ice on the surface melts and just before the glacial runoff turns the water its famous cloudy turquoise color.

node.text: Photo by @sarah_stacke / In a magical moment to behold, wild horses drink from the Moreau River on the Cheyenne River Reservation, a sovereign Lakota nation in the state of South Dakota. The Moreau is a tributary of the Missouri River, which forms the reservation's eastern boundary. For more on this story, click the link in our bio. #WildHorses #CheyenneRiverReservation #Lakota #SouthDakota #MoreauRiver

node.text:
Photo by @mattborowick / My first time seeing an active volcano in person was at the Geldingadalir eruption site on the Reykjanes Peninsula, southwestern Iceland. It’s hard to describe the feeling I had while watching it at this distance. Magical is the only word that makes sense, since the eruption posed no immediate danger to anyone at the time. The volcano has been active for the past four months and shows no signs of slowing down. 
Please follow @mattborowick for more pictures like this. #iceland #volcano #nature #adventure #summe

node.text:
Photo by @amivitale / Orphaned baby elephants walk through the 975,000-acre swath of thorny scrubland in northern Kenya known as the Namunyak Wildlife Conservancy where their home, Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e), is situated. Reteti is the first ever community-owned elephant sanctuary in Africa. It provides a safe place for injured elephants to heal and later be returned back to the wild. 
Please follow @amivitale and @r.e.s.c.u.e to learn how to support the sanctuary. @sararafoundation @conservationorg @kenyawildlifeservice @nrt_kenya  @tusk_org @sandiegozoo @thephotosociety #elephant #saveelephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / In the summer of 2019 Gina Moseley, a professor at the University of Innsbruck and the leader of the Greenland Caves Project, led a team of 10 scientists—including glaciologists, paleo-geochronologists, a microbiologist, permafrost experts, explorers, photographers, and a medical doctor—to study and sample the remote landscape of an area in the northeast corner of Greenland in Kronprins Christian Land.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on July 27, 2021. May be an image of emperor penguin.

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / During a visit to the emperor penguin colony at Snow Hill Island in Antarctica, I had the great opportunity to photograph this cute little chick winking at me. We tend to anthropomorphize animal behavior. This has happened ever since Charles Darwin first described recording emotions like joy and love among animals. Since then, the debate has evolved and expanded widely. While humankind was once thought to be the only species able to think, with feelings and emotions, we now have proof that some species have strong social behaviors. Some are capable of compassion and anger and can even grieve the loss of a family member or one of their own. Even though anthropomorphizing animal behavior can sometimes lead to misunderstanding biological behavior, I think it helps people connect with animals.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #penguin #emperorpenguin #Antarctica #conservation #wildlifephotography
